# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nb-iot-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] The **3rd Generation Partnership Project** (**3GPP**) is an umbrella term for a number of standards organizations which develop protocols for mobile telecommunications.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] 3GPP is a partnership project whose partners are its Organizational Partners (OPs), which are seven national or regional telecommunication standards organizations, and its Market Representation Partners (MRPs), which are a variety of other organizations.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] 3GPP organizes its work into three different streams: Radio Access Networks (TSG RAN), Services and Systems Aspects (TSG SA), and Core Network and Terminals (TSG CT).
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] The project was established in December 1998 with the goal of developing a specification for a 3G mobile phone system based on the 2G GSM system, within the scope of the International Telecommunication Union's International Mobile Telecommunications-2000, hence the name 3GPP.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] It should not be confused with now discontinued 3rd Generation Partnership Project 2 (3GPP2), which shadowed the 3GPP work to continue the development of a competing 3G system, CDMA2000.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] The 3GPP administrative support team (known as the "Mobile Competence Centre") is located at the European Telecommunications Standards Institute headquarters in the Sophia Antipolis technology park in France.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] The seven 3GPP Organizational Partners are from Asia, Europe and North America.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] 3GPP standards are structured as *Releases*.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] Discussion of 3GPP thus frequently refers to the functionality in one release or another.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] Each release incorporates hundreds of individual technical specification and technical report documents, each of which may have been through many revisions.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] Current 3GPP standards incorporate the latest revision of the GSM standards.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] The documents are made available without charge on 3GPP's web site.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] The technical specifications cover not only the radio part ("*air interface*") and core network, but also billing information and speech coding down to source code level.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] Cryptographic aspects (such as authentication, confidentiality) are also specified.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] The 3GPP specification work is done in Technical Specification Groups (TSGs) and Working Groups (WGs).
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] The closure of GERAN was announced in January 2016.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] The specification work on legacy GSM/EDGE system was transferred to RAN WG, RAN6.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] The 3GPP structure also includes a Project Coordination Group, which is the highest decision-making body.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] Its missions include the management of overall timeframe and work progress.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] 3GPP standardization work is contribution-driven.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] Companies ("individual members") participate through their membership to a 3GPP organizational partner.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] As of December 2020, 3GPP is composed of 719 individual members.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] Test specifications are sometimes defined as stage 4, as they follow stage 3.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] Specifications are grouped into releases.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] A release consists of a set of internally consistent set of features and specifications.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] Timeframes are defined for each release by specifying freezing dates.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] Once a release is frozen, only essential corrections are allowed (i.e. addition and modifications of functions are forbidden).
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] Freezing dates are defined for each stage.
[src:nb-iot-deep/3gpp] The 3GPP specifications are transposed into deliverables by the organizational partners.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] A **cellular network** or **mobile network** is a telecommunications network where the link to and from end nodes is wireless and the network is distributed over land areas called ***cells***, each served by at least one fixed-location transceiver (such as a base station).
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] These base stations provide the cell with the network coverage which can be used for transmission of voice, data, and other types of content via radio waves.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Each cell's coverage area is determined by factors such as the power of the transceiver, the terrain, and the frequency band being used.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] A cell typically uses a different set of frequencies from neighboring cells, to avoid interference and provide guaranteed service quality within each cell.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] When joined, these cells provide radio coverage over a wide geographic area.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The design of cellular networks allows for seamless handover, enabling uninterrupted communication when a device moves from one cell to another.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Modern cellular networks utilize advanced technologies such as Multiple Input Multiple Output (MIMO), beamforming, and small cells to enhance network capacity and efficiency.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Major telecommunications providers have deployed voice and data cellular networks over most of the inhabited land area of Earth.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] This allows mobile phones and other devices to be connected to the public switched telephone network and public Internet access.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] In addition to traditional voice and data services, cellular networks now support internet of things (IoT) applications, connecting devices such as smart meters, vehicles, and industrial sensors.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The evolution of cellular networks from 1G to 5G has progressively introduced faster speeds, lower latency, and support for a larger number of devices, enabling advanced applications in fields such as healthcare, transportation, and smart cities.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] In a cellular radio system, a land area to be supplied with radio service is divided into cells in a pattern dependent on terrain and reception characteristics.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] These cell patterns roughly take the form of regular shapes, such as hexagons, squares, or circles although hexagonal cells are conventional.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Each of these cells is assigned with multiple frequencies (*f*1 – *f*6) which have corresponding radio base stations.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The group of frequencies can be reused in other cells, provided that the same frequencies are not reused in adjacent cells, which would cause co-channel interference.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] This strategy is viable because a given radio frequency can be reused in a different area for an unrelated transmission.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] In contrast, a single transmitter can only handle one transmission for a given frequency.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Inevitably, there is some level of interference from the signal from the other cells which use the same frequency.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Consequently, there must be at least one cell gap between cells which reuse the same frequency in a standard frequency-division multiple access (FDMA) system.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Consider the case of a taxi company, where each radio has a manually operated channel selector knob to tune to different frequencies.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] As drivers move around, they change from channel to channel.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The drivers are aware of which frequency approximately covers some area.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] When they do not receive a signal from the transmitter, they try other channels until finding one that works.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The taxi drivers only speak one at a time when invited by the base station operator.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] This is a form of time-division multiple access (TDMA).
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The idea to establish a standard cellular phone network was first proposed on December 11, 1947.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] This proposal was put forward by Douglas H.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Ring, a Bell Labs engineer, in an internal memo suggesting the development of a cellular telephone system by AT&T.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The first commercial cellular network, the 1G generation, was launched in Japan by Nippon Telegraph and Telephone (NTT) in 1979, initially in the metropolitan area of Tokyo.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] However, NTT did not initially commercialize the system; the early launch was motivated by an effort to understand a practical cellular system rather than by an interest to profit from it.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] In 1981, the Nordic Mobile Telephone system was created as the first network to cover an entire country.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The network was released in 1981 in Sweden and Norway, then in Finland and Denmark in early 1982.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Televerket, a state-owned corporation responsible for telecommunications in Sweden, launched the system.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] In September 1981, Jan Stenbeck, a financier and businessman, launched Comvik, a Swedish telecommunications company.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Comvik was the first European telecommunications firm to challenge the state's telephone monopoly on the industry.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] According to sources, Comvik was the first to launch a commercial automatic cellular system before Televerket launched its own in October 1981.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] However, at the time of the new network's release, the Swedish Post and Telecom Authority threatened to shut down the system after claiming that the company had used an unlicensed automatic gear that could interfere with its own networks.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] In December 1981, Sweden awarded Comvik with a license to operate its own automatic cellular network in the spirit of market competition.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] First-generation cellular network technology continued to expand its reach to the rest of the world.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] In 1990, Millicom Inc., a telecommunications service provider, strategically partnered with Comvik's international cellular operations to become Millicom International Cellular SA.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The company went on to establish a 1G systems foothold in Ghana, Africa under the brand name Mobitel.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] In 2006, the company's Ghana operations were renamed to Tigo.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The wireless revolution began in the early 1990s, leading to the transition from analog to digital networks.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The MOSFET invented at Bell Labs between 1955 and 1960, was adapted for cellular networks by the early 1990s, with the wide adoption of power MOSFET, LDMOS (RF amplifier), and RF CMOS (RF circuit) devices leading to the development and proliferation of digital wireless mobile networks.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The first commercial digital cellular network, the 2G generation, was launched in 1991.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] This sparked competition in the sector as the new operators challenged the incumbent 1G analog network operators.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] With FDMA, the transmitting and receiving frequencies used by different users in each cell are different from each other.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Each cellular call was assigned a pair of frequencies (one for base to mobile, the other for mobile to base) to provide full-duplex operation.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The original AMPS systems had 666 channel pairs, 333 each for the CLEC "A" system and ILEC "B" system.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The number of channels was expanded to 416 pairs per carrier, but ultimately the number of RF channels limits the number of calls that a cell site could handle.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] FDMA is a familiar technology to telephone companies, which used frequency-division multiplexing to add channels to their point-to-point wireline plants before time-division multiplexing rendered FDM obsolete.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] With TDMA, the transmitting and receiving time slots used by different users in each cell are different from each other.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] TDMA typically uses digital signaling to store and forward bursts of voice data that are fit into time slices for transmission, and expanded at the receiving end to produce a somewhat normal-sounding voice at the receiver.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] TDMA must introduce latency (time delay) into the audio signal.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] As long as the latency time is short enough that the delayed audio is not heard as an echo, it is not problematic.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] TDMA is a familiar technology for telephone companies, which used time-division multiplexing to add channels to their point-to-point wireline plants before packet switching rendered TDM obsolete.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The principle of CDMA is based on spread spectrum technology developed for military use during World War II and improved during the Cold War into direct-sequence spread spectrum that was used for early CDMA cellular systems and Wi-Fi.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] DSSS allows multiple simultaneous phone conversations to take place on a single wideband RF channel, without needing to channelize them in time or frequency.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Although more sophisticated than older multiple access schemes (and unfamiliar to legacy telephone companies because it was not developed by Bell Labs), CDMA has scaled well to become the basis for 3G cellular radio systems.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Other available methods of multiplexing such as MIMO, a more sophisticated version of antenna diversity, combined with active beamforming provides much greater spatial multiplexing ability compared to original AMPS cells, that typically only addressed one to three unique spaces.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Massive MIMO deployment allows much greater channel reuse, thus increasing the number of subscribers per cell site, greater data throughput per user, or some combination thereof.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Quadrature Amplitude Modulation (QAM) modems offer an increasing number of bits per symbol, allowing more users per megahertz of bandwidth (and decibels of SNR), greater data throughput per user, or some combination thereof.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The key characteristic of a cellular network is the ability to reuse frequencies to increase both coverage and capacity.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] As described above, adjacent cells must use different frequencies, however, there is no problem with two cells sufficiently far apart operating on the same frequency, provided the masts and cellular network users' equipment do not transmit with too much power.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The elements that determine frequency reuse are the reuse distance and the reuse factor.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] where *R* is the cell radius and *N* is the number of cells per cluster.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Cells may vary in radius from 1 to 30 kilometres (0.62 to 18.64 mi).
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The boundaries of the cells can also overlap between adjacent cells and large cells can be divided into smaller cells.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The frequency reuse factor is the rate at which the same frequency can be used in the network.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] It is *1/K* (or *K* according to some books) where *K* is the number of cells which cannot use the same frequencies for transmission.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Common values for the frequency reuse factor are 1/3, 1/4, 1/7, 1/9 and 1/12 (or 3, 4, 7, 9 and 12, depending on notation).
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] In case of *N* sector antennas on the same base station site, each with different direction, the base station site can serve N different sectors.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] A **reuse pattern** of *N/K* denotes a further division in frequency among *N* sector antennas per site.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Some current and historical reuse patterns are 3/7 (North American AMPS), 6/4 (Motorola NAMPS), and 3/4 (GSM).
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] If the total available bandwidth is *B*, each cell can only use a number of frequency channels corresponding to a bandwidth of *B/K*, and each sector can use a bandwidth of *B/NK*.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Code-division multiple access-based systems use a wider frequency band to achieve the same rate of transmission as FDMA, but this is compensated for by the ability to use a frequency reuse factor of 1, for example using a reuse pattern of 1/1.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] In other words, adjacent base station sites use the same frequencies, and the different base stations and users are separated by codes rather than frequencies.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] While *N* is shown as 1 in this example, that does not mean the CDMA cell has only one sector, but rather that the entire cell bandwidth is also available to each sector individually.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Recently also orthogonal frequency-division multiple access based systems such as LTE are being deployed with a frequency reuse of 1.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Since such systems do not spread the signal across the frequency band, inter-cell radio resource management is important to coordinate resource allocation between different cell sites and to limit the inter-cell interference.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] There are various means of inter-cell interference coordination (ICIC) already defined in the standard.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Coordinated scheduling, multi-site MIMO or multi-site beamforming are other examples for inter-cell radio resource management that might be standardized in the future.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Cell towers frequently use a directional signal to improve reception in higher-traffic areas.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] In the United States, the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) limits omnidirectional cell tower signals to 100 watts of power.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] If the tower has directional antennas, the FCC allows the cell operator to emit up to 500 watts of effective radiated power (ERP).
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Although the original cell towers created an even, omnidirectional signal, were at the centers of the cells and were omnidirectional, a cellular map can be redrawn with the cellular telephone towers located at the corners of the hexagons where three cells converge.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Each tower has three sets of directional antennas aimed in three different directions with 120 degrees for each cell (totaling 360 degrees) and receiving/transmitting into three different cells at different frequencies.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] This provides a minimum of three channels, and three towers for each cell and greatly increases the chances of receiving a usable signal from at least one direction.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The numbers in the illustration are channel numbers, which repeat every 3 cells.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Large cells can be subdivided into smaller cells for high volume areas.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Cell phone companies also use this directional signal to improve reception along highways and inside buildings like stadiums and arenas.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Practically every cellular system has some kind of broadcast mechanism.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] This can be used directly for distributing information to multiple mobiles.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Commonly, for example in mobile telephony systems, the most important use of broadcast information is to set up channels for one-to-one communication between the mobile transceiver and the base station.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The three different paging procedures generally adopted are sequential, parallel and selective paging.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Paging takes place by sending the broadcast message to all of those cells.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Paging messages can be used for information transfer.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] This happens in pagers, in CDMA systems for sending SMS messages, and in the UMTS system where it allows for low downlink latency in packet-based connections.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] In LTE/4G, the Paging procedure is initiated by the MME when data packets need to be delivered to the UE.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] In a primitive taxi system, when the taxi moved away from a first tower and closer to a second tower, the taxi driver manually switched from one frequency to another as needed.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] If communication was interrupted due to a loss of a signal, the taxi driver asked the base station operator to repeat the message on a different frequency.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] In a cellular system, as the distributed mobile transceivers move from cell to cell during an ongoing continuous communication, switching from one cell frequency to a different cell frequency is done electronically without interruption and without a base station operator or manual switching.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Typically, a new channel is automatically selected for the mobile unit on the new base station which will serve it.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The mobile unit then automatically switches from the current channel to the new channel and communication continues.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The exact details of the mobile system's move from one base station to the other vary considerably from system to system (see the example below for how a mobile phone network manages handover).
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The most common example of a cellular network is a mobile phone (cell phone) network.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] A mobile phone is a portable telephone which receives or makes calls through a cell site (base station) or transmitting tower.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Radio waves are used to transfer signals to and from the cell phone.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Modern mobile phone networks use cells because radio frequencies are a limited, shared resource.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Cell-sites and handsets change frequency under computer control and use low power transmitters so that the usually limited number of radio frequencies can be simultaneously used by many callers with less interference.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] A cellular network is used by the mobile phone operator to achieve both coverage and capacity for their subscribers.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Large geographic areas are split into smaller cells to avoid line-of-sight signal loss and to support a large number of active phones in that area.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] All of the cell sites are connected to telephone exchanges (or switches), which in turn connect to the public telephone network.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] In cities, each cell site may have a range of up to approximately 1⁄2 mile (0.80 km), while in rural areas, the range could be as much as 5 miles (8.0 km).
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] It is possible that in clear open areas, a user may receive signals from a cell site 25 miles (40 km) away.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] In rural areas with low-band coverage and tall towers, basic voice and messaging service may reach 50 miles (80 km), with limitations on bandwidth and number of simultaneous calls.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Since almost all mobile phones use cellular technology, including GSM, CDMA, and AMPS (analog), the term "cell phone" is in some regions, notably the US, used interchangeably with "mobile phone".
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] However, satellite phones are mobile phones that do not communicate directly with a ground-based cellular tower but may do so indirectly by way of a satellite.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The transition from existing analog to the digital standard followed a very different path in Europe and the US.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] As a consequence, multiple digital standards surfaced in the US, while Europe and many countries converged towards the GSM standard.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] This network is the foundation of the GSM system network.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] There are many functions that are performed by this network in order to make sure customers get the desired service including mobility management, registration, call set-up, and handover.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Any phone connects to the network via an RBS (Radio Base Station) at a corner of the corresponding cell which in turn connects to the Mobile switching center (MSC).
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The MSC provides a connection to the public switched telephone network (PSTN).
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The link from a phone to the RBS is called an *uplink* while the other way is termed *downlink*.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Radio channels effectively use the transmission medium through the use of the following multiplexing and access schemes: frequency-division multiple access (FDMA), time-division multiple access (TDMA), code-division multiple access (CDMA), and space-division multiple access (SDMA).
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] As the phone user moves from one cell area to another cell while a call is in progress, the mobile station will search for a new channel to attach to in order not to drop the call.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Once a new channel is found, the network will command the mobile unit to switch to the new channel and at the same time switch the call onto the new channel.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] With CDMA, multiple CDMA handsets share a specific radio channel.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The signals are separated by using a pseudonoise code (PN code) that is specific to each phone.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] As the user moves from one cell to another, the handset sets up radio links with multiple cell sites (or sectors of the same site) simultaneously.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] This is known as "soft handoff" because, unlike with traditional cellular technology, there is no one defined point where the phone switches to the new cell.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] In IS-95 inter-frequency handovers and older analog systems such as NMT it will typically be impossible to test the target channel directly while communicating.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] In this case, other techniques have to be used such as pilot beacons in IS-95.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] This means that there is almost always a brief break in the communication while searching for the new channel followed by the risk of an unexpected return to the old channel.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] If there is no ongoing communication or the communication can be interrupted, it is possible for the mobile unit to spontaneously move from one cell to another and then notify the base station with the strongest signal.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The effect of frequency on cell coverage means that different frequencies serve better for different uses.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Low frequencies, such as 450 MHz NMT, serve very well for countryside coverage.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] GSM 900 (900 MHz) is suitable for light urban coverage.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] GSM 1800 (1.8 GHz) starts to be limited by structural walls.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] UMTS, at 2.1 GHz is quite similar in coverage to GSM 1800.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Higher frequencies are a disadvantage when it comes to coverage, but it is a decided advantage when it comes to capacity.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Picocells, covering e.g. one floor of a building, become possible, and the same frequency can be used for cells which are practically neighbors.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] Cell service area may also vary due to interference from transmitting systems, both within and around that cell.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] This is true especially in CDMA based systems.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] The receiver requires a certain signal-to-noise ratio, and the transmitter should not send with too high transmission power in view to not cause interference with other transmitters.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] As the receiver moves away from the transmitter, the power received decreases, so the power control algorithm of the transmitter increases the power it transmits to restore the level of received power.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] As the interference (noise) rises above the received power from the transmitter, and the power of the transmitter cannot be increased anymore, the signal becomes corrupted and eventually unusable.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] In CDMA-based systems, the effect of interference from other mobile transmitters in the same cell on coverage area is very marked and has a special name, *cell breathing*.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] One can see examples of cell coverage by studying some of the coverage maps provided by real operators on their web sites or by looking at independently crowdsourced maps such as Opensignal or CellMapper.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] In certain cases they may mark the site of the transmitter; in others, it can be calculated by working out the point of strongest coverage.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] A cellular repeater is used to extend cell coverage into larger areas.
[src:nb-iot-deep/cellular-network] They range from wideband repeaters for consumer use in homes and offices to smart or digital repeaters for industrial needs.
[src:nb-iot-deep/low-power-wide-area-network] A **low-power, wide-area network** (**LPWAN** or **LPWA network**) is a type of wireless telecommunication wide area network designed to allow long-range communication at a low bit rate between IoT devices, such as sensors operated on a battery.
[src:nb-iot-deep/low-power-wide-area-network] Low power, low bit rate, and intended use distinguish this type of network from a wireless WAN that is designed to connect users or businesses, and carry more data, using more power.
[src:nb-iot-deep/low-power-wide-area-network] The LPWAN data rate ranges from 0.3 kbit/s to 50 kbit/s per channel.
[src:nb-iot-deep/low-power-wide-area-network] A LPWAN may be used to create a private wireless sensor network, but may also be a service or infrastructure offered by a third party, allowing the owners of sensors to deploy them in the field without investing in gateway technology.
[src:nb-iot-deep/low-power-wide-area-network] **Power:** LPWAN manufacturers claim years to decades of usable life from built-in batteries, but real-world application tests have not confirmed this.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] In telecommunications, **Long Term Evolution** (**LTE**) is a standard for wireless broadband communication for cellular mobile devices and data terminals.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] It is considered to be a "transitional" 4G technology, and is therefore also referred to as **3.95G** as a step above 3G.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] LTE is based on the 2G GSM/EDGE and 3G UMTS/HSPA standards.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] It improves on those standards' capacity and speed by using a different radio interface and core network improvements.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] LTE is the upgrade path for carriers with both GSM/UMTS networks and CDMA2000 networks.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] LTE has been succeeded by LTE Advanced, which is officially defined as a "true" 4G technology and also named "LTE+".
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] The standard is developed by the 3GPP (3rd Generation Partnership Project) and is specified in its Release 8 document series, with minor enhancements described in Release 9.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] LTE is also called **3.95G** and has been marketed as **4G LTE** and **Advanced 4G**; but the original version did not meet the technical criteria of a 4G wireless service, as specified in the 3GPP Release 8 and 9 document series for LTE Advanced.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] The LTE Advanced standard formally satisfies the ITU-R requirements for being considered IMT-Advanced.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] To differentiate LTE Advanced and WiMAX-Advanced from the then current 4G technologies, ITU has defined in January 2012 the latter as "True 4G".
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] LTE stands for Long Term Evolution and is a registered trademark owned by ETSI (European Telecommunications Standards Institute) for the wireless data communications technology and development of the GSM/UMTS standards.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] However, other nations and companies do play an active role in the LTE project.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] The goal of LTE was to increase the capacity and speed of wireless data networks using new DSP (digital signal processing) techniques and modulations that were developed around the turn of the millennium.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] A further goal was the redesign and simplification of the network architecture to an IP-based system with significantly reduced transfer latency compared with the 3G architecture.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] The LTE wireless interface is incompatible with 2G and 3G networks, so it must be operated on a separate radio spectrum.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] The idea of LTE was first proposed in 1998, with the use of the COFDM radio access technique to replace the CDMA and studying its Terrestrial use in the L band at 1428 MHz (TE) In 2004 by Japan's NTT Docomo, with studies on the standard officially commenced in 2005.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] In May 2007, the LTE/SAE Trial Initiative (LSTI) alliance was founded as a global collaboration between vendors and operators with the goal of verifying and promoting the new standard to ensure the global introduction of the technology as quickly as possible.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] The LTE standard was finalized in December 2008, and the first publicly available LTE service was launched by TeliaSonera in Oslo and Stockholm on December 14, 2009, as a data connection with a USB modem.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] In Canada, Rogers Wireless was the first to launch LTE network on July 7, 2011, offering the Sierra Wireless AirCard 313U USB mobile broadband modem, known as the "LTE Rocket stick" then followed closely by mobile devices from both HTC and Samsung.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] The next version of LTE is LTE Advanced, which was standardized in March 2011.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] Additional evolution known as LTE Advanced Pro was approved in 2015.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] The LTE specification provides downlink peak rates of 300 Mbit/s, uplink peak rates of 75 Mbit/s, and QoS provisions permitting a transfer latency of less than 5 ms in the radio access network.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] LTE has the ability to manage fast-moving mobiles and supports multicast and broadcast streams.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] LTE supports scalable carrier bandwidths, from 1.4 MHz to 20 MHz and supports both frequency division duplexing (FDD) and time-division duplexing (TDD).
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] The IP-based network architecture, called the Evolved Packet Core (EPC) designed to replace the GPRS Core Network, supports seamless handovers for both voice and data to cell towers with older network technology such as GSM, UMTS and CDMA2000.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] The simpler architecture results in lower operating costs (for example, each E-UTRA cell will support up to four times the data and voice capacity supported by HSPA).
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] Because LTE frequencies and bands differ from country to country, only multi-band phones can use LTE in all countries where it is supported.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] Most carriers supporting GSM or HSUPA networks can be expected to upgrade their networks to LTE at some stage.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] The following is a list of the top 10 countries/territories by 4G LTE coverage as measured by OpenSignal.com in February/March 2019.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] For the complete list of all the countries/territories, see list of countries by 4G LTE penetration.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] There are two major differences between LTE-TDD and LTE-FDD: how data is uploaded and downloaded, and what frequency spectra the networks are deployed in.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] While LTE-FDD uses paired frequencies to upload and download data, LTE-TDD uses a single frequency, alternating between uploading and downloading data through time.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] The ratio between uploads and downloads on a LTE-TDD network can be changed dynamically, depending on whether more data needs to be sent or received.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] LTE-TDD and LTE-FDD also operate on different frequency bands, with LTE-TDD working better at higher frequencies, and LTE-FDD working better at lower frequencies.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] Frequencies used for LTE-TDD range from 1850 MHz to 3800 MHz, with several different bands being used.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] The LTE-TDD spectrum is generally cheaper to access, and has less traffic.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] Further, the bands for LTE-TDD overlap with those used for WiMAX, which can easily be upgraded to support LTE-TDD.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] Despite the differences in how the two types of LTE handle data transmission, LTE-TDD and LTE-FDD share 90 percent of their core technology, making it possible for the same chipsets and networks to use both versions of LTE.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] A number of companies produce dual-mode chips or mobile devices, including Samsung and Qualcomm, while operators CMHK and Hi3G Access have developed dual-mode networks in Hong Kong and Sweden, respectively.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] The creation of LTE-TDD involved a coalition of international companies that worked to develop and test the technology.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] China Mobile was an early proponent of LTE-TDD, along with other companies like Datang Telecom and Huawei, which worked to deploy LTE-TDD networks, and later developed technology allowing LTE-TDD equipment to operate in white spaces—frequency spectra between broadcast TV stations.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] Intel also participated in the development, setting up a LTE-TDD interoperability lab with Huawei in China, as well as ST-Ericsson, Nokia, and Nokia Siemens (now Nokia Solutions and Networks), which developed LTE-TDD base stations that increased capacity by 80 percent and coverage by 40 percent.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] Qualcomm also participated, developing the world's first multi-mode chip, combining both LTE-TDD and LTE-FDD, along with HSPA and EV-DO.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] Accelleran, a Belgian company, has also worked to build small cells for LTE-TDD networks.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] Trials of LTE-TDD technology began as early as 2010, with Reliance Industries and Ericsson India conducting field tests of LTE-TDD in India, achieving 80 megabit-per second download speeds and 20 megabit-per-second upload speeds.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] By 2011, China Mobile began trials of the technology in six cities.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] Although initially seen as a technology utilized by only a few countries, including China and India, by 2011 international interest in LTE-TDD had expanded, especially in Asia, in part due to LTE-TDD's lower cost of deployment compared to LTE-FDD.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] By the middle of that year, 26 networks around the world were conducting trials of the technology.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] The Global LTve (GTI) was also started in 2011, with founding partners China Mobile, Bharti Airtel, SoftBank Mobile, Vodafone, Clearwire, Aero2 and E-Plus.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] In September 2011, Huawei announced it would partner with Polish mobile provider Aero2 to develop a combined LTE-TDD and LTE-FDD network in Poland, and by April 2012, ZTE Corporation had worked to deploy trial or commercial LTE-TDD networks for 33 operators in 19 countries.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] In late 2012, Qualcomm worked extensively to deploy a commercial LTE-TDD network in India, and partnered with Bharti Airtel and Huawei to develop the first multi-mode LTE-TDD smartphone for India.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] In Japan, SoftBank Mobile launched LTE-TDD services in February 2012 under the name **Advanced eXtended Global Platform** (AXGP), and marketed as SoftBank 4G (ja).
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] The AXGP band was previously used for Willcom's PHS service, and after PHS was discontinued in 2010 the PHS band was re-purposed for AXGP service.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] In the U.S., Clearwire planned to implement LTE-TDD, with chipmaker Qualcomm agreeing to support Clearwire's frequencies on its multi-mode LTE chipsets.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] With Sprint's acquisition of Clearwire in 2013, the carrier began using these frequencies for LTE service on networks built by Samsung, Alcatel-Lucent, and Nokia.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] As of March 2013, 156 commercial 4G LTE networks existed, including 142 LTE-FDD networks and 14 LTE-TDD networks.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] As of November 2013, the South Korean government planned to allow a fourth wireless carrier in 2014, which would provide LTE-TDD services, and in December 2013, LTE-TDD licenses were granted to China's three mobile operators, allowing commercial deployment of 4G LTE services.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] In January 2014, Nokia Solutions and Networks indicated that it had completed a series of tests of voice over LTE (VoLTE) calls on China Mobile's TD-LTE network.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] The next month, Nokia Solutions and Networks and Sprint announced that they had demonstrated throughput speeds of 2.6 gigabits per second using a LTE-TDD network, surpassing the previous record of 1.6 gigabits per second.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] Much of the LTE standard addresses the upgrading of 3G UMTS to what will eventually be 4G mobile communications technology.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] A large amount of the work is aimed at simplifying the architecture of the system, as it transitions from the existing UMTS circuit + packet switching combined network to an all-IP flat architecture system.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] The LTE standard supports only packet switching with its all-IP network.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] Voice calls in GSM, UMTS, and CDMA2000 are circuit switched, so with the adoption of LTE, carriers will have to re-engineer their voice call network.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] In this approach, LTE just provides data services, and when a voice call is to be initiated or received, it will fall back to the circuit-switched domain.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] , and therefore, can provide services quickly.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] However, the disadvantage is a longer call setup delay.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] In this approach, the handset works simultaneously in the LTE and circuit-switched modes, with the LTE mode providing data services and the circuit-switched mode providing the voice service.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] The disadvantage of this solution is that the phone can become expensive with high power consumption.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] One additional approach that is not initiated by operators is the usage of over-the-top content (OTT) services, using applications like Skype and Google Talk to provide LTE voice service.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] Most major backers of LTE preferred and promoted VoLTE from the beginning.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] The lack of software support in initial LTE devices, as well as core network devices, however, led to a number of carriers promoting VoLGA (Voice over LTE Generic Access) as an interim solution.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] The idea was to use the same principles as GAN (Generic Access Network, also known as UMA or Unlicensed Mobile Access), which defines the protocols through which a mobile handset can perform voice calls over a customer's private Internet connection, usually over wireless LAN.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] VoLGA however never gained much support, because VoLTE (IMS) promises much more flexible services, albeit at the cost of having to upgrade the entire voice call infrastructure.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] VoLTE may require Single Radio Voice Call Continuity (SRVCC) to be able to smoothly perform a handover to a 2G or 3G network in case of poor LTE signal quality.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] While the industry has standardized on VoLTE, early LTE deployments required carriers to introduce circuit-switched fallback as a stopgap measure.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] When placing or receiving a voice call on a non-VoLTE-enabled network or device, LTE handsets will fall back to old 2G or 3G networks for the duration of the call.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] To ensure compatibility, 3GPP demands at least AMR-NB codec (narrow band), but the recommended speech codec for VoLTE is Adaptive Multi-Rate Wideband, also known as HD Voice.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] This codec is mandated in 3GPP networks that support 16 kHz sampling.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] Fraunhofer IIS has proposed and demonstrated "Full-HD Voice", an implementation of the AAC-ELD (Advanced Audio Coding – Enhanced Low Delay) codec for LTE handsets.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] Where previous cell phone voice codecs only supported frequencies up to 3.5 kHz and upcoming wideband audio services branded as *HD Voice* up to 7 kHz, Full-HD Voice supports the entire bandwidth range from 20 Hz to 20 kHz.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] For end-to-end Full-HD Voice calls to succeed, however, both the caller's and recipient's handsets, as well as networks, have to support the feature.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] As a result, phones from one country may not work in other countries.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] Users will need a multi-band capable phone for roaming internationally.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] According to the European Telecommunications Standards Institute's (ETSI) intellectual property rights (IPR) database, about 50 companies have declared, as of March 2012, holding essential patents covering the LTE standard.
[src:nb-iot-deep/lte-telecommunication] This is less than the combined published rates, due to reduced-rate licensing agreements, such as cross-licensing.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] More recent machine to machine communication has changed into a system of networks that transmits data to personal appliances.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] The expansion of IP networks has made M2M communication quicker and easier while using less power, and it is a component of the Internet of Things (IoT).
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] These networks also allow new business opportunities for consumers and suppliers.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Wired communication machines have been using signaling to exchange information since the early 20th century.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Machine to machine has taken more sophisticated forms since the advent of computer networking automation and predates cellular communication.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] It has been utilized in applications such as telemetry, industrial, automation, and SCADA.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Machine to machine devices that combined telephony and computing were first conceptualized by Theodore Paraskevakos while working on his Caller ID system in 1968, later patented in the U.S. in 1973.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] This system, similar but distinct from the panel call indicator of the 1920s and automatic number identification of the 1940s, which communicated telephone numbers to machines, was the predecessor to what is now caller ID, which communicates numbers to people.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] After several attempts and experiments, he realized that in order for the telephone to be able to read the caller's telephone number, it must possess intelligence so he developed the method in which the caller's number is transmitted to the called receiver's device.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] His portable transmitter and receiver were reduced to practice in 1971 in a Boeing facility in Huntsville, Alabama, representing the world's first working prototypes of caller identification devices (shown at right).
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] They were installed at Peoples' Telephone Company in Leesburg, Alabama and in Athens, Greece where they were demonstrated to several telephone companies with great success.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] This method was the basis for modern-day Caller ID technology.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] He was also the first to introduce the concepts of intelligence, data processing and visual display screens into telephones which gave rise to the smartphone.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] In 1977, Paraskevakos started Metretek, Inc. in Melbourne, Florida to conduct commercial automatic meter reading and load management for electrical services which led to the "smart grid" and "smart meter".
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] To achieve mass appeal, Paraskevakos sought to reduce the size of the transmitter and the time of transmission through telephone lines by creating a single chip processing and transmission method.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Motorola was contracted in 1978 to develop and produce the single chip, but the chip was too large for Motorola's capabilities at that time.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] As a result, it became two separate chips (shown at right).
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] While cellular is becoming more common, many machines still use landlines (POTS, DSL, cable) to connect to the IP network.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] The first M1 module was used for early point of sale (POS) terminals, in vehicle **telematics**, remote monitoring and **track and trace** applications.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Machine to machine technology was first embraced by early implementers such as GM and Hughes Electronics Corporation who realized the benefits and future potential of the technology.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] By 1997, machine to machine wireless technology became more prevalent and sophisticated as ruggedized modules were developed and launched for the specific needs of different vertical markets such as automotive telematics.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Another example of an early use is OnStar's **vehicle tracking system**.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] The hardware components of a machine to machine network are manufactured by a few key players.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] In 1998, Quake Global started designing and manufacturing machine to machine satellite and terrestrial modems.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Initially relying heavily on the Orbcomm network for its satellite communication services, Quake Global expanded its telecommunication product offerings by engaging both satellite and terrestrial networks, which gave Quake Global an edge in offering network-neutral products.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] In 2004, Digi International began producing wireless gateways and routers.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Shortly after in 2006, Digi purchased Max Stream, the manufacturer of XBee radios.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] These hardware components allowed users to connect machines no matter how remote their location.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Since then, Digi has partnered with several companies to connect hundreds of thousands of devices around the world.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] In 2004, Christopher Lowery, a UK telecoms entrepreneur, founded Wyless Group, one of the first Mobile Virtual Network Operators (MVNO) in the M2M space.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Operations began in the UK and Lowery published several patents introducing new features in data protection & management, including Fixed IP Addressing combined with Platform Managed Connectivity over VPNs.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] The company expanded to the US in 2008 and became T-Mobile's largest partners on both sides of the Atlantic.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] In 2006, Machine-to-Machine Intelligence (M2Mi) Corp started work with NASA to develop automated machine to machine intelligence.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Automated machine to machine intelligence enables a wide variety of mechanisms including wired or wireless tools, sensors, devices, server computers, robots, spacecraft and grid systems to communicate and exchange information efficiently.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] In 2009, AT&T and Jasper Technologies, Inc. entered into an agreement to support the creation of machine to machine devices jointly.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] They have stated that they will be trying to drive further connectivity between consumer electronics and machine to machine wireless networks, which would create a boost in speed and overall power of such devices.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] 2009 also saw the introduction of real-time management of GSM and CDMA network services for machine to machine applications with the launch of the PRiSMPro™ Platform from machine to machine network provider KORE Telematics.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] The platform focused on making multi-network management a critical component for efficiency improvements and cost-savings in machine to machine device and network usage.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Also in 2009, Wyless Group introduced PORTHOS™, its multi-operator, multi-application, device agnostic Open Data Management Platform.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] The company introduced a new industry definition, Global Network Enabler, comprising customer-facing platform management of networks, devices and applications.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Also in 2009, the Norwegian incumbent Telenor concluded ten years of machine to machine research by setting up two entities serving the upper (services) and lower (connectivity) parts of the value-chain.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Telenor Connexion in Sweden draws on Vodafone's former research capabilities in subsidiary Europolitan and is in Europe's market for services across such typical markets as logistics, **fleet management**, car safety, healthcare, and smart metering of electricity consumption.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Telenor Objects has a similar role supplying connectivity to machine to machine networks across Europe.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] In the UK, Business MVNO Abica, commenced trials with Telehealth and Telecare applications which required secure data transit via Private APN and HSPA+/4G LTE connectivity with static IP address.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] In early 2010 in the U.S., AT&T, KPN, Rogers, Telcel / America Movil and Jasper Technologies, Inc. began to work together in the creation of a machine to machine site, which will serve as a hub for developers in the field of machine to machine communication electronics.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] In January 2011, Aeris Communications, Inc. announced that it is providing machine to machine telematics services for Hyundai Motor Corporation.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Partnerships like these make it easier, faster and more cost-efficient for businesses to use machine to machine.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] In June 2010, mobile messaging operator Tyntec announced the availability of its high-reliability SMS services for M2M applications.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Later that year, KORE acquired Australia-based Mach Communications Pty Ltd. in response to increased M2M demand within Asia-Pacific markets.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] In April 2011, Ericsson acquired Telenor Connexion's machine to machine platform, in an effort to get more technology and know-how in the growing sector.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] In August 2011, Ericsson announced that they have successfully completed the asset purchase agreement to acquire Telenor Connexion's (machine to machine) technology platform.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] According to the independent wireless analyst firm Berg Insight, the number of cellular network connections worldwide used for machine to machine communication was 47.7 million in 2008.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] The company forecasts that the number of machine to machine connections will grow to 187 million by 2014.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] A research study from the E-Plus Group shows that in 2010 2.3 million machine to machine smart cards will be in the German market.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] According to the study, this figure will rise in 2013 to over 5 million smart cards.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] The main growth driver is segment "tracking and tracing" with an expected average growth rate of 30 percent.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] The fastest growing M2M segment in Germany, with an average annual growth of 47 percent, will be the consumer electronics segment.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] In April 2013, OASIS MQTT standards group is formed with the goal of working on a lightweight publish/subscribe reliable messaging transport protocol suitable for communication in M2M/IoT contexts.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] IBM and StormMQ chair this standards group and Machine-to-Machine Intelligence (M2Mi) Corp is the secretary.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] In May 2014, the committee published the MQTT and NIST Cybersecurity Framework Version 1.0 committee note to provide guidance for organizations wishing to deploy MQTT in a way consistent with the NIST Framework for Improving Critical Infrastructure Cybersecurity.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] In May 2013, machine to machine network service providers KORE Telematics, Oracle, Deutsche Telekom, Digi International, Orbcomm and Telit formed the International Machine to Machine Council (IMC).
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] The first trade organization to service the entire machine to machine ecosystem, the IMC aims at making machine to machine ubiquitous by helping companies install and manage the communication between machines.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Wireless networks that are all interconnected can serve to improve production and efficiency in various areas, including machinery that works on building cars and on letting the developers of products know when certain products need to be taken in for maintenance and for what reason.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Such information serves to streamline products that consumers buy and works to keep them all working at highest efficiency.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Another application is to use wireless technology to monitor systems, such as utility meters.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] This would allow the owner of the meter to know if certain elements have been tampered with, which serves as a quality method to stop fraud.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] In Quebec, Rogers will connect Hydro Quebec's central system with up to 600 Smart Meter collectors, which aggregate data relayed from the province's 3.8-million Smart Meters.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] In the UK, Telefónica won on a €1.78 billion ($2.4 billion) smart-meter contract to provide connectivity services over a period of 15 years in the central and southern regions of the country.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] The contract is the industry's biggest deal yet.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Some companies, such as M-kopa in Kenya, are using M2M to enforce a payment plan, by turning off its customers' solar devices remotely for non-payment.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] "Our loan officer is that SIM card in the device that can shut it off remotely," says Chad Larson, M-Kopa's finance director and its third co-founder, when describing the technology.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] A third application is to use wireless networks to update digital billboards.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] This allows advertisers to display different messages based on time of day or day-of-week, and allows quick global changes for messages, such as pricing changes for gasoline.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] The industrial machine to machine market is undergoing a fast transformation as enterprises are increasingly realizing the value of connecting geographically dispersed people, devices, sensors and machines to corporate networks.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Today, industries such as oil and gas, precision agriculture, military, government, smart cities/municipalities, manufacturing, and public utilities, among others, utilize machine to machine technologies for a myriad of applications.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Many companies have enabled complex and efficient data networking technologies to provide capabilities such as high-speed data transmission, mobile mesh networking, and 3G/4G cellular backhaul.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Machine to machine wireless networks can serve to improve the production and efficiency of machines, to enhance the reliability and safety of complex systems, and to promote the life-cycle management for key assets and products.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] The application of intelligent analysis tools and Device-to-Business (D2B) TM informatics platform form the basis of e-maintenance machine network that can lead to near-zero downtime performance of machines and systems.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] The e-maintenance machine network provides integration between the factory floor system and e-business system, and thus enables the real time decision making in terms of near-zero downtime, reducing uncertainties and improved system performance.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] In addition, with the help of highly interconnected machine networks and advance intelligent analysis tools, several novel maintenance types are made possible nowadays.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] For instance, the distant maintenance without dispatching engineers on-site, the online maintenance without shutting down the operating machines or systems, and the predictive maintenance before a machine failure become catastrophic.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] All these benefits of e-maintenance machine network add up improve the maintenance efficiency and transparency significantly.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] As described in, The framework of e-maintenance machine network consists of sensors, data acquisition system, communication network, analytic agents, decision-making support knowledge base, information synchronization interface and e-business system for decision making.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Initially, the sensors, controllers and operators with data acquisition are used to collect the raw data from equipment and send it out to Data Transformation Layer automatically via internet or intranet.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] The Data Transform Layer then employs signal processing tools and feature extraction methods to convert the raw data into useful information.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] This converted information often carries rich information about the reliability and availability of machines or system and is more agreeable for intelligent analysis tools to perform subsequent process.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] The Synchronization Module and Intelligent Tools comprise the major processing power of the e-maintenance machine network and provide optimization, prediction, clustering, classification, bench-marking and so on.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] The results from this module can then be synchronized and shared with the e-business system on for decision making.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] In real application, the synchronization module will provide connection with other departments at the decision making level, like enterprise resource planning (ERP), customer relation management (CRM) and supply chain management (SCM).
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Another application of machine to machine network is in the health management for a fleet of similar machines using clustering approach.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] This method was introduced to address the challenge of developing fault detection models for applications with non-stationary operating regimes or with incomplete data.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] The overall methodology consists of two stages: 1) Fleet Clustering to group similar machines for sound comparison; 2) Local Cluster Fault Detection to evaluate the similarity of individual machines to the fleet features.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] The purpose of fleet clustering is to aggregate working units with similar configurations or working conditions into a group for sound comparison and subsequently create local fault detection models when global models cannot be established.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Within the framework of peer to peer comparison methodology, the machine to machine network is crucial to ensure the instantaneous information share between different working units and thus form the basis of fleet level health management technology.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] The fleet level health management using clustering approach was patented for its application in wind turbine health monitoring after validated in a wind turbine fleet of three distributed wind farms.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Different with other industrial devices with fixed or static regimes, wind turbine's operating condition is greatly dictated by wind speed and other ambient factors.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Even though the multi-modeling methodology can be applicable in this scenario, the number of wind turbines in a wind farm is almost infinite and may not present itself as a practical solution.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Instead, by leveraging on data generated from other similar turbines in the network, this problem can be properly solved and local fault detection models can be effective built.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] The results of wind turbine fleet level health management reported in demonstrated the effectiveness of applying a cluster-based fault detection methodology in the wind turbine networks.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Fault detection for a horde of industrial robots experiences similar difficulties as lack of fault detection models and dynamic operating condition.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Industrial robots are crucial in automotive manufacturing and perform different tasks as welding, material handling, painting, etc.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] In this scenario, robotic maintenance becomes critical to ensure continuous production and avoid downtime.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Historically, the fault detection models for all the industrial robots are trained similarly.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Critical model parameters like training samples, components, and alarming limits are set the same for all the units regardless of their different functionalities.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] Even though these identical fault detection models can effectively identify faults sometimes, numerous false alarms discourage users from trusting the reliability of the system.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] However, within a machine network, industrial robots with similar tasks or working regimes can be group together; the abnormal units in a cluster can then be prioritized for maintenance via training based or instantaneous comparison.
[src:nb-iot-deep/machine-to-machine] This peer to peer comparison methodology inside a machine network could improve the fault detection accuracy significantly.
[src:nb-iot-deep/narrowband-iot] NB-IoT focuses specifically on indoor coverage, long battery life, and high connection density.
[src:nb-iot-deep/narrowband-iot] NB-IoT uses a subset of the LTE standard, but limits the bandwidth to a single narrow-band of 200 kHz.
[src:nb-iot-deep/narrowband-iot] It uses OFDM modulation for downlink communication and SC-FDMA for uplink communications.
[src:nb-iot-deep/narrowband-iot] IoT applications which require more frequent communications will be better served by LTE-M, which has no duty cycle limitations operating on the licensed spectrum.
[src:nb-iot-deep/narrowband-iot] LTE-M is also more suited for applications in moving devices.
[src:nb-iot-deep/narrowband-iot] In March 2019, the Global Mobile Suppliers Association (GSA) announced that over 100 operators had either NB-IoT or LTE-M networks.
[src:nb-iot-deep/narrowband-iot] This number had risen to 142 deployed/launched networks by September 2019.
[src:nb-iot-deep/narrowband-iot] The 3GPP-compliant LPWA device ecosystem continues to grow.
[src:nb-iot-deep/narrowband-iot] In April 2019, GSA identified 210 devices supporting either Cat-NB1/NB-2 or Cat-M1 – more than double the number in its GAMBoD database at the end of March 2018.
[src:nb-iot-deep/narrowband-iot] This figure had risen a further 50% by September 2019, with a total of 303 devices identified as supporting either Cat-M1, Cat-NB1 (NB-IoT) or Cat-NB2.
[src:nb-iot-deep/narrowband-iot] Of these, 230 devices support Cat-NB1 (including known variants) and 198 devices support Cat-M1 (including known variants).
[src:nb-iot-deep/narrowband-iot] The split of devices (as of September 2019) was 60.4% modules, 25.4% asset trackers, and 5.6% routers, with data loggers, femtocells, smart-home devices, and smart watches, USB modems, and vehicle on-board units (OBUs), making up the balance.
[src:nb-iot-deep/narrowband-iot] In 2018 first NB-IoT data loggers and other certified devices started to appear.
[src:nb-iot-deep/narrowband-iot] For example ThingsLog released their first CE certified single channel NB-IoT data logger on Tindie in late 2018.
[src:nb-iot-deep/narrowband-iot] To integrate NB-IoT into a maker board for IoT developments, SODAQ, a Dutch IoT hardware and software engineering company, crowdfunded an NB-IoT shield on Kickstarter.
[src:nb-iot-deep/narrowband-iot] They then went on to partner with module manufacturer u-blox to create maker boards with NB-IoT and LTE-M integrated.
[src:nb-iot-deep/narrowband-iot] Since 2021, there also is a cheap all-in-one NB-IoT solution available to the general public developed by the Chinese manufacturer Ai-Thinker.
[src:nb-iot-deep/narrowband-iot] At the beginning of 2023 the Belgian company DPTechnics released the Walter IoT board which combines an ESP32-S3 together with a Sequans Monarch 2 NB-IoT/LTE-M platform.
[src:nb-iot-deep/narrowband-iot] The board is focused on long-term availability and includes a GNSS receiver.
